It is in really good shape cosmetically, it has never been carried so there is no holster wear but it does have a small spot here or there (there are a couple of very small marks on the front of the trigger guard where I used to have a laser mounted).  It has had less than 1000 rounds through it and it feeds flawlessly. It has been a home defense gun and safe queen its whole life - I pull it out every couple of years, fire a box of ammo through it, clean it and put it back. I recently used it for range time at a concealed carry class and at 7 yds I was putting 5 rounds through practically the same hole with cheap white box Remington ammo. I put Pachmeyer grips on it the day I bought it so the original walnut grips (pictured) are pristince. It will also include a few extras: an extended stainless threaded target barrel and compensated slide extension. title: For Sale:  1956 Sino-Soviet SKS / Scarce!
postcontent: 1956 Sino-Soviet SKS......the rarest of ALL the Chinese Type 56 rifles.Made in Russia and assembled in China.In 1956 Russia closed the Tula arsenal and moved all the equipment,workers,and unassembled parts to China.The first rifles assembled were called Sino-Soviet "Letter" guns.These rifles had a serial number consisiting of a letter,and followed by 4 digits.Many also had arsenal 26 stamp,but no Chinese symbols.Additional featrues were threded barrels with long lugs.So long they almost met the sight base band.They also used blade bayonets and had "PotBelly" stocks.Very rare and very collectible.Though all the military built Chinese SKS were of high quality,the early rifles are the most sought after.All numbers match except dust cover/stock which were probably arsenal replaced.M6300 stamped on receiver-bolt carrier-trigger-magazine......I`m an FFL in Port St Lucie.Please view my other collectible rifles and pistols.

title: For Sale:   WINCHESTER  Model 1895 Takedown in 405 caliber
postcontent: This a very desirable Winchester Model 1895 Takedown sporting rifle chambered in the most sought after 405 caliber. This rifle, serial #81870 was manufactured in 1913. The gun comes with a special order Takedown feature, factory sling swivels and I believe a factory installed Lyman receiver sight with windage adjustment. The .405 was introduced in 1904.The Winchester .405 is, at least for me personally the medicine gun for lions!" The .405 was discontinued in 1932. As for condition the receiver retains most of its toning original blue finish. The original 24" tapered round barrel retains 95% of its original bluing. The original walnut stocks are in very good condition, The action is tight and smooth, mechanically perfect. The bore is MINTY, showing a mirror with sharp rifling. I would rate it at 95%+. The barrel address and caliber markings are perfect. The screws are very good and most remain unturned. The special order Lyman receiver with a windage adjustment is marked "95". The Takedown mechanism locks up tight. In all this old gun still retains a lot of condition, with an excellent bore that would make this rifle a great addition to ones collection.
